Perfect! Now I have all the information I need. Let me create a comprehensive summary document:

## OpenClaw Channel Plugin Architecture & Structure

Based on my thorough exploration of the OpenClaw repository, here's a complete guide to understanding and replicating the channel plugin pattern.

---

## 1. BUNDLED WORKSPACE PLUGIN TREE

### Directory Structure
All bundled channel plugins live in `/extensions/` directory:

```
extensions/
├── irc/              ← Classic IRC networks
├── nostr/            ← Nostr (NIP-04 encrypted DMs)
├── matrix/           ← Matrix protocol
├── discord/          ← Discord
├── slack/            ← Slack
├── telegram/         ← Telegram
├── whatsapp/         ← WhatsApp
├── bluebubbles/      ← BlueBubbles (Apple Messages)
├── zalo/             ← Zalo
└── zalouser/         ← Zalo User variant
```

These are **production-ready bundled plugins** treated as if they were third-party plugins from the boundary perspective.

---

## 2. REFERENCE PLUGIN: IRC (Complete File Structure)

### Root-Level Files (9 files)
```
extensions/irc/
├── index.ts                    ← Main plugin entry
├── api.ts                      ← Public API barrel
├── setup-entry.ts              ← Setup-only entry point
├── channel-config-api.ts        ← Config API exports
├── package.json                ← NPM package metadata
├── openclaw.plugin.json        ← Plugin manifest
└── src/                        ← Implementation directory
    ├── accounts.ts             ← Account resolution & listing
    ├── channel.ts              ← Main ChannelPlugin definition
    ├── client.ts               ← IRC protocol client
    ├── config-schema.ts        ← Zod validation schema
    ├── config-ui-hints.ts      ← UI hints for config
    ├── connect-options.ts      ← Connection options builder
    ├── control-chars.ts        ← IRC control character handling
    ├── inbound.ts              ← Message inbound handling
    ├── monitor.ts              ← Provider monitoring loop
    ├── normalize.ts            ← Target/allowlist normalization
    ├── policy.ts               ← Policy resolution
    ├── probe.ts                ← Status probing
    ├── protocol.ts             ← IRC protocol implementation
    ├── runtime.ts              ← Runtime store
    ├── runtime-api.ts          ← Private runtime barrel
    ├── send.ts                 ← Outbound message sending
    ├── setup-core.ts           ← Setup implementation
    ├── setup-surface.ts        ← Setup wizard UI
    ├── types.ts                ← TypeScript type definitions
    └── [test files]            ← Unit/integration tests
```

---

## 3. REFERENCE PLUGIN: NOSTR (Simpler Example)

Nostr is a more minimal direct-DM-only channel plugin (14 files):

```
extensions/nostr/
├── index.ts                         ← Main entry
├── api.ts                           ← Minimal API (re-exports runtime-api)
├── setup-entry.ts                   ← Setup entry
├── setup-api.ts                     ← Setup API exports
├── test-api.ts                      ← Test helper exports
├── runtime-api.ts                   ← Runtime barrel
├── package.json
├── openclaw.plugin.json
├── README.md
├── CHANGELOG.md
└── src/
    ├── channel.ts                   ← Main plugin definition
    ├── types.ts                     ← Account types & resolution
    ├── config-schema.ts             ← Zod schema + profiles
    ├── runtime.ts                   ← Runtime store
    ├── nostr-bus.ts                 ← Relay bus abstraction
    ├── nostr-profile.ts             ← Profile management
    ├── nostr-profile-http.ts        ← HTTP handler for profiles
    ├── nostr-profile-import.ts      ← Profile import utilities
    ├── nostr-state-store.ts         ← State persistence
    ├── default-relays.ts            ← Default relay URLs
    ├── setup-surface.ts             ← Setup wizard
    ├── session-route.ts             ← Session routing
    ├── seen-tracker.ts              ← Message deduplication
    ├── metrics.ts                   ← Status metrics
    ├── test-fixtures.ts             ← Test helpers
    └── [test files]
```

**Key Difference from IRC:** Nostr uses `createTopLevelChannelConfigAdapter` (simpler, single account) vs IRC's `createScopedChannelConfigAdapter` (multiple accounts support).

